Be a nerd with me for a bit & check out the different species of trilobites I turned into rings. Trilobites are my favorite fossil. The first creature to develop an ocular system that could define shapes, rather than just shades of light. 

Alive 520 to 250 million years ago, trilobites thrived for around 270 million years before dying off in a mass extinction event at the end of the Permian Period that  that took out 90% of the earth’s species.

Anytime the state of the planet or humanity gets me down, I think of how long these little marine arthropods flourished. The length of time that humans have been around, and the devastation we’ve created in our time here will be less than a blink of an eye in the earth’s timeline once we die. It brings me peace knowing the earth will be just fine. 

#ammonite #trilobite #electroforming #handmadejewelry

Others ways my brand is unlike fast fashion: 

My work is made to order. Fast fashion companies will make tons of items, unsold merchandise is burned or tossed into a landfill. Luxury brands also do this to maintain exclusivity and keep their prices high. This is not a practice I find to be ok in any way ~ 

I only remake items once the original ones have sold. When I have leftover inventory, (which in 10 years has happened twice), I’ve gifted it out to people. When I have leftover materials, I donate them to other people making art or to charity programs. When I stopped working with polymer clay, my materials and equipment went to an art therapy program in an assisted living facility for people struggling with mental illness. Chains I bought that were not up to my standards of quality were donated to Tinkertpoia in Tacoma (a non profit art store). 

Years ago I stopped using plastic wrap for my online orders and eventually I switched to only using recycled materials to pack my items. 

All of my copper waste is being collected to be recycled. All of my sterling silver waste is being collected so I can use it for cuttle fish casting someday. 

This is also why I got into lapidary ~ so I can source more materials for my work from local areas while also producing work that’s guaranteed more ethical. 

These are not things I promote or talk about often. All you need to know is that I have a deep love and reverence for the earth ~ I also love making jewelry.  So I do my best to make art in the least damaging way possible and it’s always my goal to make work that lasts for years or a lifetime.

Although there is no ethical consumption under capitalism, you do have power to limit your impact on the planet with the brands you support and the items you buy ❤️🧚💕 ~ xoxo Erika #smallbusiness #shoplocal #ethicalfashion #stopfastfashion
